{"id":"2208.03962","submitter":"Irina Bobkova V","authors":"G.A. Bobkov, I.V. Bobkova, A.M. Bobkov, Akashdeep Kamra","title":"N\\'eel proximity effect at antiferromagnet/superconductor interfaces","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 106, 144512 (2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.106.144512","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Spin-splitting induced in a conventional superconductor weakens\nsuperconductivity by destroying spin-singlet and creating spin-triplet Cooper\npairs. We demonstrate theoretically that such an effect is also caused by an\nadjacent compensated antiferromagnet, which yields no net spin-splitting. We\nfind that the antiferromagnet produces N\\'eel triplet Cooper pairs, whose\npairing amplitude oscillates rapidly in space similar to the antiferromagnet's\nspin. The emergence of these unconventional Cooper pairs reduces the singlet\npairs' amplitude, thereby lowering the superconducting critical temperature. We\ndevelop a quasiclassical Green's functions description of the system employing\na two-sublattice framework. It successfully captures the rapid oscillations in\nthe Cooper pairs' amplitude at the lattice spacing scale as well as their\nsmooth variation on the larger coherence length scale. Employing the\ntheoretical framework thus developed, we investigate this N\\'eel proximity\neffect in a superconductor/antiferromagnet bilayer as a function of interfacial\nexchange, disorder, and chemical potential, finding rich physics. Our findings\nalso offer insights into experiments which have found a larger than expected\nsuppression of superconductivity by an adjacent antiferromagnet.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Aug 2022 08:12:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-04"}
