{"id":"2208.04096","submitter":"Zhichao Zhou","authors":"Zhichao Zhou, Yuming Zhou, Chunrong Fang, Zhenyu Chen, Yutian Tang","title":"Selectively Combining Multiple Coverage Goals in Search-Based Unit Test\n  Generation","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1145/3551349.3556902","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.SE","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Unit testing is a critical part of software development process, ensuring the\ncorrectness of basic programming units in a program (e.g., a method).\nSearch-based software testing (SBST) is an automated approach to generating\ntest cases. SBST generates test cases with genetic algorithms by specifying the\ncoverage criterion (e.g., branch coverage). However, a good test suite must\nhave different properties, which cannot be captured by using an individual\ncoverage criterion. Therefore, the state-of-the-art approach combines multiple\ncriteria to generate test cases. As combining multiple coverage criteria brings\nmultiple objectives for optimization, it hurts the test suites' coverage for\ncertain criteria compared with using the single criterion. To cope with this\nproblem, we propose a novel approach named \\textbf{smart selection}. Based on\nthe coverage correlations among criteria and the coverage goals' subsumption\nrelationships, smart selection selects a subset of coverage goals to reduce the\nnumber of optimization objectives and avoid missing any properties of all\ncriteria. We conduct experiments to evaluate smart selection on $400$ Java\nclasses with three state-of-the-art genetic algorithms. On average, smart\nselection outperforms combining all goals on $65.1\\%$ of the classes having\nsignificant differences between the two approaches.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Aug 2022 12:30:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-10"}
